data.title: A perfect jewel...
data.text: Elsa's is an an absolute gem. Small but brilliant. It's a cozy little restaurant tucked in Downtown Overland Park. Totally unassuming. I believe a husband & wife run everything (kitchen, wait staff, etc) between the two of them. The portions are extremely generous. We had the chicken, beef, & lamb tibbs. It was excellent. The collar greens are outstanding. Definitely try the tea. It was the star of my meal. Service is leisurely as is the norm in most non-Western cultures. Sit back, relax, & enjoy the experience.

data.title: It was fun to try something new
data.text: Friends introduced us to this fun little restaurant. The owner was friendly and taught us how to eat Ethiopian.  It was a pleasant new experience for us.  The Chef made us a special sampler plate because we were new to Ethiopian food.  It is a lot of food and fed the 5 of us with some to spare.

data.title: Dinner
data.text: Fabulous!  The service was excellent;  Our server helped us choose the right food and showed us how to eat with the bread.  The chef came out to make sure we were satisfied.  Hands down, an excellent choice!  Very affordable as well!

data.title: Special Lunch
data.text: We wanted something unique for a special family lunch. This was it! Plenty of parking, good location. Owners are very friendly and helpful! The samosas were excellent!

data.title: 5 Reasons to Come Here
data.text:
You will enjoy visiting this place if:
1. You like authentic home made style food
2. You are in the mood to dine in a small friendly casual place
3. You have time if you need to wait a bit longer
4. You are visiting downtown of Overland Park and want something different than BBQ :)

We loved the wonderfully cooked meat, soft sour bread, and spicy side dishes. The owners are very friendly to the regulars and the new visitors like us. Elsa came to ask us if we enjoyed her cooking and tried to teach my husband how to eat the beef tips just using hands - wrap the meat in bread. Sweet touch.
The prices are very reasonable and the portions are generous.

The service is very friendly, but keep in mind that you might wait if the restaurant is full.

The only "bit of disappointment" is the desserts are not authentic.

We definitely will be back to try more! Thank you, Elsa!

data.title: A MUST TRY
data.text:
It's a small and quaint little restaurant tucked along a long line of store fronts in Overland Park. The menu is straight forward and doesn't go into detail of what everything is exactly, but don't worry, it all tastes delicious! 

We ordered a sampling of a great many different words we couldn't pronounce and proceeded to eat it all with a fork like the novices we were. Thankfully the proprietor saw us and came to our rescue. He explained how to use their unique and mouth pleasing bread, called injera, as the utensil with which you eat. 

The cook, (I think it was Elsa herself!) came out after a little while and expounded upon how everything there was made from scratch and completely gluten free just by happenstance of how it's all made, which amazed me. I stuffed myself and didn't feel yucky afterwards. Tons of vegetarian options too. I look forward to going again.

data.title: Love this place
data.text: My wife and I never tired Ethopian food before and we nervous about it. However, it was the best decision we made in our trip in Kansas City. The food was unique but wonderful and would recommend to anyone who enjoys eating different types of cuisines.

data.title: Wonderful Food at Amazing Prices
data.text: My wife and I had been planning on trying this restaurant for sometime now. We wish we had done so a while ago! Excellent food. Succulent lamb, delicious injera, at prices that are a fraction of other KC area Ethiopian restaurants charge.  The owners are charming and the location is great.

data.title: AMAZING, AMAZING, AMAZING!
data.text:
I will definitely be returning to Elsa's. Even if the food hadn't been fantastic (which it was!) I would still be back for another cup of coffee. It is one of the BEST cups of coffee I have ever had in my life, and I'm a total coffee snob.

The iced tea was delicious - filled with spices and chilled to perfection. We ordered the meat platter that had small samples of 3 of the meat dishes. I loved every single one. I also recommend the lentils and potato side dishes!

Overall, this was a fabulous experience and I can't say enough good things. Elsa and her husband (i think he's her husband) were so friendly and the food was delicious. I'll definitely be a regular.

data.title: Fantastic and Unique, Will be Back!
data.text: I felt adventurous the other day, and wanted to try something new in the Overland Park area, so I stopped in Elsa's Ethiopian Restaurant. I've never had food from Ethiopia, so I was curious and had no idea what to expect. I ordered the Sambosa as an appetizer and they were delicious. For the main meal, I ordered the Lamb and my Girlfriend had the chicken, both were excellent! We got all the sides so we could try everything. The experience was so unique, no forks! You just use the bread to scoop up the food, it was great! The meat was nicely cooked and seasoned, and the sides were very flavorful! The owners were so nice, she was very generous and helpful! I still think about Elsa's and can't wait to go back! Highly recommended!!

data.title: Wonderful!
data.text: The food was delicious, and the owners were extremely hospitable. I would especially recommend the Doro Wat. Overall, it felt like a truly authentic experience. Warm, friendly, and cosy. I'm sure Elsa is doing Ethiopia proud!

data.title: Cross cultural experience
data.text: One visit can only provide one perspective.  There was some quirkiness from our perspective which now doubt stems from the mixing of cultures.   The absolute deliciousness of the food makes some of the strange experiences charming.   For example there was only one server on a Friday night.  We took the last empty table.  A couple came in a little after us and the server told them to sit at a table which had dirty dishes on it.   It was some time before he cleared the table.   My friend ordered a honey wine.  When we asked for a straw we were flatly told this was not the right way.   The couple next to us asked for a fork and they were told this was not the right way to eat the food.     By now we all learned this was a cultural thing.  The server took great pride in his food and the culture.  He explained how to eat the food using the soft flat bread to pick up the food and dip it in the homemade cheese.      My advice is you decide to go is roll with things don't try to change or adapt to it what your used to.  The server  seems honored if you ask for explanation or recommendation.  In this night the wait was long but worth it.  The honey wine was different and some will like it and all should try.  All the food is tasty and filling and the experience is unique.   You won't break the bank either.

data.title: Good Stuff
data.text: Never had Ethiopian food prior to this visit. Pretty good! I believe I had the dorowat. My husband was in love though! You get lots of food but don't use a fork! The lady of the house will be quick to correct you. Lol

data.title: Around the world in Johnson County
data.text: I visited Elsa's for the first time with a friend.  We were warmly greeted and waited on immediately.  The menu had a large variety of foods. We ordered a platter that had a variety of meats and vegetables that was plenty big enough for two.  We were given an explanation as to what foods we were eating.  Our hosts even graciously offered to show us how to eat the food with the Injera.(Ethiopian Bread)  Everything was delicious including the Baklava which was also big enough for two.  Would definitely recommend and would definitely like to return.

data.title: Check their hours!
data.text: We made a point to go to Elsa's when we came to KC for the baseball game however when we arrived, there was a handwritten note on the door stating they were closed that day.  Disappointed that we made a point to visit the restaurant only to find it closed.

data.title: Great Ethiopian food
data.text: I have had Ethiopian food in numerous countries but I can honestly say this is authentic Ethiopian food. The service was good, family ran small restaurant, very clean with plenty of parking in the area. The price is fair as well for the large portions you will receive.

data.title: Excellent Ethiopian!!
data.text: The food here is excellent!  You can't go wrong with any selection off of the menu, even the vegetarian items!  If all vegetarian foods tasted this good I would consider converting!  The portions are enough for two meals.  Also, Elsa makes you feel like a member of the family!! That's great customer service!!! You have to try this restaurant!!!!

data.title: First time
data.text: Eating ethiopian food. I don't really know what to make of it. I do like the flavors and textures. We shared the combo platter as Elsa recommended. The injera is their potatoes or rice. It's similar to a pancake. It has a neutral taste but nice texture. As Elsa said- you have to dunk it over the beef or chicken or lentil and scoop then put in your mouth. You use your fingers to eat which I am not new to. The beef is spicy and savory. The chicken, lentils and sambosa are all good.

data.title: Love the food!
data.text: We love going to the farmers market on Saturday and then stopping by Elsa's for lunch.  They have wonderful dishes.  Our favorites are the combos so we can get different tastes on one plate.

data.title: Fun
data.text: I had never tried Ethiopian food, so I jumped at the chance when I was in KC for business.  The place is not huge, but the food is delicious, and the staff is very attentive.  The food is not really spicy compared to Indian, for example.  I like sharing.  The portions are huge.  I'd go again if I was in town
